<DOC><DOCNO> AP881018-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1954EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Brazil     10-18 0330</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-Brazil,0339</SECOND><HEAD>Gorbachev Praises Democratic Trends in Latin America</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday welcomedwhat he said was a trend toward democracy in Latin America andcited a plebiscite in Chile as the latest example, Tass reported.   The Soviet news agency said Gorbachev made the remarks in aspeech at a Kremlin dinner for President Jose Sarney of Brazil.   ``Brazil's turn for democracy has been welcomed in the SovietUnion,'' Tass quoted Gorbachev as saying. ``It has represented apowerful factor in a general tendency typical of Latin America overrecent years.''   Tass said Gorbachev then noted the Oct. 5 plebiscite in Chileand said it was part of the trend toward democracy in Latin America.   ``The decisive popular `no' to the dictatorship in Chile hasreflected it graphically,'' Gorbachev told Sarney, according toTass.   In the Chilean plebiscite, more than 3.9 million people votedagainst the proposal that President Augusto Pinochet remain inpower until 1997. The ``yes'' vote was 3.1 million. Gen. Pinochet,the army commander, has ruled Chile with a military governmentsince leading a 1973 coup that overthrew the government of electedPresident Salvador Allende, a Marxist.   Sarney became Brazil's first civilian president in 1985 after 21years of right-wing military rule. From 1964-85, Brazil shunnedhigh-level contacts with the Soviet Union but maintained trade anddiplomatic ties.   Sarney, who arrived Monday for a three-day stay, is the firstBrazilian head of state to visit the Soviet Union.   In his dinner speech, Gorbachev said Brazil and the Soviet Unionshould work together to preserve their vast forests. He said thatmaintaining the great wooded areas of Siberia in the Soviet Unionand the Amazon River basin in Brazil ``is our common duty bothbefore the people of our countries and before mankind.''   The Soviet leader also called for increased economic andcultural ties and joint work in space.   In his speech, Sarney called for increasing political, trade andcultural ties.</TEXT></DOC>